## Investigation
- @google/adk base_agent.d.ts: `readonly subAgents: BaseAgent[]` (class prop,
  line 87, non-optional; the `?` at line 31 is on the CONFIG input only) and
  `findAgent(name): BaseAgent | undefined` (line 153, always a method).
- base_agent.js constructor line 32: `this.subAgents = config.subAgents || [];`
  => a REAL ADK agent ALWAYS has subAgents as an array and findAgent as a method.
  So both guards are genuinely redundant in production (Dan is right).
- findAgent impl (base_agent.js:115-135): recurses subAgent.findAgent(name) with
  NO visited/cycle guard. => it throws (stack overflow / RangeError) exactly when
  the agent graph is CYCLIC. That is the answer to comment 3, and our manual walk
  (which HAS a `visited` Set) is the cycle-safe fallback. So the try/catch stays
  and is now documented.

## Resolution
- Removed both guards; call root.findAgent(name) directly and
  queue.push(...agent.subAgents) directly. Reworded the docstring (no longer
  'when present' since findAgent is always present) and the catch comment to
  state the cyclic-overflow rationale.
- Note ADK itself iterates `this.subAgents` with no Array.isArray guard
  (findSubAgent), confirming the type is trustworthy.

## Errors & mistakes
- First run after removing the guards: jest FAILED 1/24 —
  'agents outside the agent tree nest under the innermost open tool span'
  threw `TypeError: agent.subAgents is not iterable`. Root cause: the
  invocationContext() test helper (test line ~181) mocked the root agent as a
  bare {name, description} literal — no subAgents, no findAgent. The removed
  guards had been silently papering over an UNREALISTIC mock.
  - Why only that one test failed: findAgentInTree returns at `agent.name ===
    name` before reaching the subAgents push whenever the target IS the root
    (agentName defaults to 'agent_a' = root.name). Only the 'outside_agent'
    case (target != root.name, not in tree) reaches `...agent.subAgents` and
    blew up.
- Fix: made the mock faithful to the real ADK shape — added `subAgents: []` and
  a leaf `findAgent: (n) => n === 'agent_a' ? agent : undefined`. This also
  keeps the try/catch's documented purpose honest (it no longer fires on every
  unit test just because the mock lacked findAgent).

## Dead ends / decisions
- Considered adding ONLY `subAgents: []` to the mock (minimal). Rejected: the
  mock would still lack findAgent, so root.findAgent(name) would throw+be caught
  on EVERY callback unit test, contradicting the catch comment that says it's for
  cyclic overflow. Gave the mock a realistic findAgent instead.
- Considered using a real LlmAgent for invocationContext().agent. Rejected as
  overkill — these are plugin-callback unit tests that deliberately avoid a
  runner/model; a faithful literal is enough.
- Did NOT touch the `queue.shift()!` non-null assertion (loop guarantees
  non-empty; Dan didn't flag it on #7305; out of scope).

